-- Module 8, Lesson 4: Troubleshooting Disapproved Ads
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Troubleshooting Disapproved Ads</h2><h3>Diagnosing and Fixing Ad Rejections</h3><p>Ad disapprovals are frustrating but usually fixable. Understanding common issues and systematic troubleshooting gets ads approved quickly. This lesson provides practical strategies for identifying problems and resolving disapprovals efficiently.</p><h3>Common Disapproval Reasons</h3><p>Prohibited content. Restricted products without compliance. Excessive text in images. Misleading claims. Landing page issues. Targeting violations. Technical errors. Identifying specific reason first step to resolution.</p><h3>Reading Disapproval Notifications</h3><p>Check notification details carefully. Identify specific policy cited. Note which element flagged. Understand exact violation. Sometimes vague, requires interpretation. Clear understanding enables targeted fix.</p><h3>Image Text Issues</h3><p>Historically 20% text rule. Now more flexible but still relevant. Excessive text reduces delivery. Use text overlay tool to check. Reduce text if flagged. Image-focused creative performs better anyway.</p><h3>Landing Page Problems</h3><p>Non-functional page. Irrelevant to ad. Missing privacy policy. Broken checkout. Slow loading. Pop-ups or redirects. Fix landing page issues. Quality landing page improves approval and performance.</p><h3>Misleading Content</h3><p>Exaggerated claims. Before/after images. Unrealistic promises. Clickbait headlines. Sensational language. Make claims accurate and substantiated. Honesty prevents disapprovals.</p><h3>Targeting Violations</h3><p>Discriminatory targeting for special categories. Age restrictions not followed. Location requirements ignored. Sensitive attribute targeting. Review targeting settings. Adjust to comply with policies.</p><h3>Trademark Issues</h3><p>Using others trademarks without permission. Brand name in ad copy. Competitor targeting concerns. Respect intellectual property. Get permission or remove references.</p><h3>Systematic Troubleshooting Process</h3><p>Read disapproval reason carefully. Review ad against policies. Check each element: image, copy, landing page, targeting. Identify likely issue. Make targeted fix. Resubmit for review. Document for learning.</p><h3>Editing and Resubmitting</h3><p>Edit ad to address specific issue. Make minimal necessary changes. Avoid completely new ad if possible. Resubmit through Ads Manager. Request manual review if appropriate. Monitor approval status.</p><h3>Requesting Manual Review</h3><p>Use if believe automated review error. Provide context and explanation. Professional, concise message. Include relevant details. Manual review takes longer. Use judiciously.</p><h3>Testing Borderline Content</h3><p>Small budget test first. Conservative approach to questionable content. Have backup creative ready. Learn from disapprovals. Adjust strategy based on feedback.</p><h3>Preventing Future Disapprovals</h3><p>Review policies before creating ads. Conservative creative choices. Quality landing pages. Accurate targeting. Regular policy updates. Learn from past disapprovals. Proactive prevention saves time.</p><h3>Working with Support</h3><p>Contact support for persistent issues. Provide all relevant information. Professional communication. Follow instructions carefully. Escalate if needed. Support can provide clarification.</p><h3>Account-Level Issues</h3><p>Sometimes disapprovals indicate account problems. Check Account Quality. Address underlying issues. Improve account health. Account-level fixes prevent future disapprovals.</p><h3>Industry-Specific Challenges</h3><p>Healthcare, finance, dating have stricter rules. Understand industry-specific requirements. Compliance documentation may be needed. Work within constraints. Specialized knowledge required.</p><h3>Learning from Patterns</h3><p>Track disapproval reasons. Identify recurring issues. Adjust processes and training. Continuous improvement. Pattern recognition prevents repeats.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Most disapprovals are fixable with targeted edits</li><li>Read disapproval notifications carefully for specific reasons</li><li>Common issues: text in images, landing pages, misleading claims</li><li>Systematic troubleshooting identifies and fixes problems</li><li>Edit minimally to address specific issue</li><li>Request manual review if believe automated error</li><li>Prevent future disapprovals through policy knowledge</li><li>Learn from patterns to improve processes</li></ul><p>Next lesson covers Navigating iOS14+ Privacy Changes.</p></div>'
WHERE title = 'Troubleshooting Disapproved Ads' AND EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM modules m JOIN courses c ON m.course_id = c.id 
    WHERE m.id = lessons.module_id AND c.title LIKE '%Facebook%Ads%Mastery%'
);

-- Module 8, Lesson 5: Navigating iOS14+ Privacy Changes
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Navigating iOS14+ Privacy Changes</h2><h3>Adapting to Privacy-First Advertising</h3><p>iOS14+ privacy changes significantly impacted Facebook advertising. App Tracking Transparency reduced data availability and attribution accuracy. Understanding these changes and adaptation strategies maintains advertising effectiveness in privacy-first environment.</p><h3>What Changed with iOS14+</h3><p>App Tracking Transparency (ATT) requires user permission. Many users opt out of tracking. Reduced data signals for optimization. Attribution windows shortened. Delayed reporting. Aggregated event measurement. Fundamental shift in data availability.</p><h3>Impact on Facebook Ads</h3><p>Less precise targeting. Reduced conversion tracking. Attribution challenges. Delayed reporting (up to 3 days). Audience size limitations. Lookalike quality affected. Performance measurement harder. Significant challenges for advertisers.</p><h3>Aggregated Event Measurement</h3><p>Limited to 8 conversion events per domain. Must prioritize events. Event configuration required. Domain verification necessary. Understanding AEM critical. Proper setup minimizes impact.</p><h3>Configuring Events</h3><p>Prioritize most valuable events. Purchase typically first priority. Add to cart, lead, view content follow. Configure in Events Manager. Domain verification required. Strategic event selection important.</p><h3>Attribution Window Changes</h3><p>7-day click default (was 28-day). 1-day view option. Shorter windows show fewer conversions. Understand what you are measuring. Consistent windows for comparison. Attribution complexity increased.</p><h3>Modeling and Estimation</h3><p>Facebook uses statistical modeling. Estimates conversions from opted-out users. Aggregated learning compensates for data loss. Not perfect but helps. Understand limitations. Modeling improves over time.</p><h3>Adaptation Strategies</h3><p>Broader targeting to maximize learning. First-party data emphasis. Email list building. Conversion API implementation. Creative quality focus. Longer-term measurement. Strategic adaptation required.</p><h3>Conversion API (CAPI)</h3><p>Server-side tracking bypasses browser limitations. Complements pixel tracking. Improves data accuracy. Requires technical implementation. Increasingly important. Priority implementation for serious advertisers.</p><h3>First-Party Data Importance</h3><p>Own your customer data. Email lists and CRM. Less dependent on platform tracking. Build direct relationships. First-party data unaffected by iOS changes. Strategic priority.</p><h3>Creative and Messaging Shifts</h3><p>Quality creative more important. Compelling offers drive action. Clear value propositions. Strong calls-to-action. Creative excellence compensates for targeting limitations. Invest in creative quality.</p><h3>Measurement Challenges</h3><p>Incomplete attribution picture. Cross-device tracking harder. Multi-touch attribution affected. Incrementality testing valuable. Marketing mix modeling. Diversified measurement approach.</p><h3>Broader Targeting Benefits</h3><p>AI learns from more data. Finds unexpected audiences. Reduces over-reliance on narrow targeting. Often performs well. Trust algorithmic optimization. Broader can be better.</p><h3>Long-Term Perspective</h3><p>Privacy changes permanent trend. Continued evolution expected. Adapt continuously. Privacy-first strategies sustainable. Early adapters gain advantage. Future-proof approach.</p><h3>Android and Other Platforms</h3><p>Android may follow iOS lead. Prepare for broader privacy changes. Platform-agnostic strategies. Diversification reduces risk. Stay informed on developments.</p><h3>Competitive Implications</h3><p>All advertisers affected. Those who adapt best win. Opportunity in change. Better creative and strategy differentiate. Privacy changes level some playing fields.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>iOS14+ ATT significantly reduced tracking and attribution</li><li>Aggregated Event Measurement limits conversion events</li><li>Configure and prioritize events strategically</li><li>Conversion API implementation critical for data accuracy</li><li>First-party data and email lists increasingly important</li><li>Broader targeting and creative quality compensate for data loss</li><li>Measurement more complex, diversified approach needed</li><li>Privacy-first trend permanent, continuous adaptation required</li></ul><p>Next module covers Real-World Case Studies & Campaign Builds.</p></div>'
WHERE title = 'Navigating iOS14+ Privacy Changes' AND EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM modules m JOIN courses c ON m.course_id = c.id 
    WHERE m.id = lessons.module_id AND c.title LIKE '%Facebook%Ads%Mastery%'
);

-- Module 9, Lesson 1: E-commerce Funnel Build (Walkthrough)
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>E-commerce Funnel Build (Walkthrough)</h2><h3>Complete Campaign Strategy from Cold to Purchase</h3><p>Building a complete e-commerce funnel requires strategic campaign layering. This walkthrough demonstrates how to structure campaigns from awareness through purchase and retention. Follow this proven framework to maximize e-commerce results on Facebook.</p><h3>Funnel Overview</h3><p>Top: Cold audience awareness. Middle: Engagement and consideration. Bottom: Conversion campaigns. Post-purchase: Retention and upsell. Each stage serves specific purpose. Coordinated funnel maximizes lifetime value.</p><h3>Top of Funnel: Awareness</h3><p>Objective: Reach or Brand Awareness. Broad targeting or interest-based. Engaging content showcasing brand and products. Video performs well. Build awareness and pixel data. Foundation for retargeting. Budget: 20-30% of total.</p><h3>Middle Funnel: Engagement</h3><p>Target: Website visitors, video viewers, engagers. Objective: Traffic or Engagement. Product-focused content. Educational and value-driven. Build consideration. Warm audience development. Budget: 20-30% of total.</p><h3>Bottom Funnel: Conversion</h3><p>Target: Add-to-cart, product viewers. Objective: Conversions or Catalog Sales. Direct response messaging. Strong offers and CTAs. Dynamic product ads. Highest intent audience. Budget: 40-50% of total.</p><h3>Cart Abandonment</h3><p>Target: Cart abandoners (last 7-14 days). Show exact abandoned products. Urgency and incentive messaging. High conversion potential. Critical for e-commerce. Dedicated budget allocation.</p><h3>Post-Purchase: Retention</h3><p>Target: Recent purchasers. Cross-sell and upsell campaigns. Thank you and onboarding content. Build loyalty. Maximize customer lifetime value. Often overlooked but valuable.</p><h3>Campaign Structure</h3><p>Separate campaigns by funnel stage. Clear naming conventions. Appropriate objectives per stage. Coordinated messaging. Proper exclusions. Organized structure enables optimization.</p><h3>Audience Strategy</h3><p>Cold: Broad, interests, lookalikes. Warm: Engagers, visitors. Hot: Cart abandoners, product viewers. Purchasers: Cross-sell audiences. Strategic segmentation. Proper exclusions prevent overlap.</p><h3>Creative Strategy</h3><p>Top: Brand story, lifestyle, education. Middle: Product benefits, social proof. Bottom: Offers, urgency, specific products. Retention: Personalized, appreciation. Match creative to funnel stage.</p><h3>Budget Allocation</h3><p>Start with conversion focus. Add upper funnel as scale. Adjust based on performance. Test different allocations. Balance short and long-term. Data-driven budget decisions.</p><h3>Measurement Framework</h3><p>Top: Reach, CPM, engagement. Middle: CTR, landing page views. Bottom: ROAS, CPA, purchases. Retention: Repeat purchase rate, LTV. Stage-appropriate metrics.</p><h3>Optimization Process</h3><p>Weekly performance reviews. Reallocate budget to winners. Refresh creative regularly. Expand winning audiences. Test new approaches. Continuous improvement cycle.</p><h3>Scaling the Funnel</h3><p>Vertical scaling within campaigns. Horizontal expansion to new audiences. Geographic expansion. Product line additions. Systematic growth approach. Maintain efficiency while scaling.</p><h3>Common Mistakes</h3><p>Conversion-only focus. Neglecting upper funnel. Poor audience exclusions. Inconsistent messaging. Insufficient creative refresh. Not tracking full funnel. Avoid these errors.</p><h3>Advanced Tactics</h3><p>Sequential messaging. Value-based lookalikes. Predictive audiences. Automated funnel optimization. Sophisticated approaches for experienced advertisers.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Complete funnel includes awareness, engagement, conversion, retention</li><li>Each stage has appropriate objective, targeting, creative</li><li>Budget allocation typically 40-50% conversion, 20-30% each for awareness and engagement</li><li>Cart abandonment campaigns critical for e-commerce</li><li>Post-purchase retention maximizes customer lifetime value</li><li>Proper exclusions prevent audience overlap</li><li>Match creative and messaging to funnel stage</li><li>Continuous optimization and testing essential</li></ul><p>Next lesson covers Local Business Lead Gen Campaign.</p></div>'
WHERE title = 'E-commerce Funnel Build (Walkthrough)' AND EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM modules m JOIN courses c ON m.course_id = c.id 
    WHERE m.id = lessons.module_id AND c.title LIKE '%Facebook%Ads%Mastery%'
);

-- Module 9, Lesson 2: Local Business Lead Gen Campaign
UPDATE lessons SET content = '<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Local Business Lead Gen Campaign</h2><h3>Generating Qualified Leads for Service Businesses</h3><p>Local service businesses have unique advertising needs. Geographic targeting, lead quality, and phone calls matter more than e-commerce metrics. This lesson provides a proven framework for local lead generation success on Facebook.</p><h3>Local Business Objectives</h3><p>Generate qualified leads. Drive phone calls. Increase store visits. Build local awareness. Appointment bookings. Different from e-commerce. Local-specific strategies required.</p><h3>Geographic Targeting</h3><p>Radius around business location. City or zip code targeting. Service area definition. Exclude too-far locations. Precise local targeting. Balance reach and relevance.</p><h3>Campaign Objective Selection</h3><p>Lead Generation for form fills. Messages for conversations. Store Traffic for visits. Calls for phone inquiries. Choose based on business model. Test different objectives.</p><h3>Lead Generation Ads</h3><p>Instant Forms capture leads on Facebook. Pre-filled information reduces friction. Custom questions qualify leads. Mobile-optimized experience. High conversion rates. Integrate with CRM.</p><h3>Click-to-Call Campaigns</h3><p>Phone call objective. Click-to-call button. Track call conversions. Ideal for service businesses. Immediate connection. High-intent leads.</p><h3>Messenger Lead Generation</h3><p>Start conversations via Messenger. Automated and human responses. Qualify leads through chat. Schedule appointments. Personal touch at scale. Growing trend for local.</p><h3>Creative for Local Businesses</h3><p>Showcase actual work and results. Local customer testimonials. Before/after where appropriate. Team and facility images. Community involvement. Local authenticity matters.</p><h3>Offer Strategy</h3><p>Free consultation or estimate. Limited-time discount. First-time customer special. Value-added bonus. Compelling offers drive action. Test different offers.</p><h3>Landing Page Best Practices</h3><p>Mobile-optimized design. Clear value proposition. Simple form (name, phone, email). Trust signals (reviews, credentials). Click-to-call prominent. Local information visible.</p><h3>Lead Quality vs Quantity</h3><p>Qualify leads through questions. Price range indication. Service area confirmation. Timeline questions. Balance volume and quality. Better leads worth higher cost.</p><h3>Follow-Up Systems</h3><p>Immediate automated response. Quick human follow-up critical. CRM integration. Lead nurture sequences. Track lead-to-customer conversion. System determines ROI.</p><h3>Measurement for Local</h3><p>Cost per lead. Lead-to-customer rate. Customer acquisition cost. Lifetime value. Phone call tracking. Appointment bookings. Revenue attribution.</p><h3>Budget Recommendations</h3><p>Start with $20-50/day minimum. Scale based on lead quality and capacity. Consider service value. High-ticket services justify higher CPA. Budget matches business capacity.</p><h3>Seasonal Considerations</h3><p>Many local businesses seasonal. Adjust campaigns accordingly. Ramp up before peak season. Maintain presence in slow periods. Seasonal strategy planning.</p><h3>Competition and Differentiation</h3><p>Highlight unique value. Credentials and experience. Customer results and reviews. Local expertise. Community connection. Stand out from competitors.</p><h3>Multi-Location Strategies</h3><p>Separate campaigns per location. Location-specific creative. Local phone numbers. Individual landing pages. Centralized management. Scale while maintaining local relevance.</p><h3>Key Takeaways</h3><ul><li>Local businesses need geographic targeting and lead quality focus</li><li>Lead Generation, Messages, and Calls are primary objectives</li><li>Instant Forms reduce friction and increase conversions</li><li>Click-to-call ideal for service businesses</li><li>Qualify leads through form questions</li><li>Quick follow-up critical for conversion</li><li>Track lead-to-customer rate and CAC</li><li>Local authenticity and differentiation important</li></ul><p>Next lesson covers Digital Product Launch Strategy.</p></div>'
WHERE title = 'Local Business Lead Gen Campaign' AND EXISTS (
    SELECT 1 FROM modules m JOIN courses c ON m.course_id = c.id 
    WHERE m.id = lessons.module_id AND c.title LIKE '%Facebook%Ads%Mastery%'
);
